an area houses roughly ten times the population of its core municipal city of Johannesburg, which contained 957,441 people as of the 2011 census.\nUrban population rate: 69% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nSouth Sudan.\nMetropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nSudan.\nUrban population rate: 48% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nTanzania.\nUrban population rate: 34% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nTogo.\nUrban population rate: 52% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nTunisia.\nUrban population rate: 72% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nUganda.\nUrban population rate: 19% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nZambia.\nUrban population rate: 44% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nZimbabwe.\nUrban population rate: 46% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nAsia.\nAfghanistan.\nUrban population rate: 29% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nArmenia.\nUrban population rate: 70% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nAzerbaijan.\nUrban population rate: 60% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nBahrain.\nUrban population rate: 80% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nBangladesh.\nIn Bangladesh, the large population centres which have significant financial, political and administrative importance are considered to be as Metropolitan cities, which are governed by City Corporations. In total, there are 12 city corporations in Bangladesh. 4 of them (Dhaka North City Corporation, Dhaka South City Corporation, Narayanganj City Corporation, Gazipur City Corporation) are part of Dhaka Metropolitan Area.\nUrban population rate: 36% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nBrunei.\nUrban population rate: 45% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nCambodia.\nUrban population rate: 26% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nChina.\nIn China, there used to be no clear distinction between megalopolis (, lit. city cluster) and metropolitan area () until National Development and Reform Commission issued \"Guidelines on the Cultivation and Development of Modern Metropolitan Areas\" () on Feb 19, 2019, in which a metropolitan area was defined as \"an urbanized spatial form in a megalopolis dominated by (a) supercity(-ies) or megacity(-ies), or a large metropolis playing a leading part, and within the basic range of 1-hour commute area.\"\nData are referred to borders determined by Sino-British Joint Declaration (1984), Sino-Portugal Joint Declaration (1987) and later agreements with countries that share a land border with China or influenced by disputes in the sea where China faces (see Territorial disputes focus).\nUrban population rate: 57% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nCyprus.\nData are referred to pre-1974 Turkish Army occupation boundaries.\nUrban population rate: 62% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nGeorgia.\nData are referret to pre-2008 Russo-Georgian War.\nUrban population rate: 60% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nIndia.\nIn India, a metropolitan city is defined as one with a population more than one million. In policing jurisdiction, state governments can declare any city or town with a population exceeding one million as a metropolitan area as per the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973.\nUrban population rate: 38% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nIndonesia.\nIn Indonesia, the government of Indonesia defines a \"metropolitan area\" as an urban agglomeration where its spatial planning is prioritised due to its highly important influence on the country. Jakarta, Surabaya, Bandung, Semarang, Medan, Makassar, Palembang are important metropolitan area in the country. Currently, there are 10 metropolitan cities in Indonesia that have been recognized by the government.\nUrban population rate: 52% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nIran.\nUrban population rate: 76% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nIraq.\nUrban population rate: 72% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nIsrael.\nData are referred to 1949 Armistice boundaries, after 1948 Arab-Israeli War.\nUrban population rate: 58% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nJapan.\nUrban population rate: 72% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nJordan.\nUrban population rate: 83% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nKazakhstan.\nUrban population rate: 66% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nKuwait.\nUrban population rate: 98% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nKyrgyzstan.\nUrban population rate: 42% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nLaos.\nUrban population rate: 43% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nLebanon.\nUrban population rate: 90% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nMalaysia + Singapore.\nUrban population rate: 77% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nMongolia.\nUrban population rate: 69% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nMyanmar.\nUrban population rate: 42% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nNepal.\nUrban population rate: 25% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nNorth Korea.\nBoundaries are referred to the Third inter-Korean summit agreement (2018).\nUrban population rate: 67% (2024). Metropolitan area population data are referred to 2024.\nOman.\nUrban population rate: 7